    <question>
        <prompt>The Scopes Trial media coverage revealed:</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Scientific consensus</option>
            <option letter="b">Urban-rural cultural divisions</option>
            <option letter="c">Educational unity</option>
            <option letter="d">Religious harmony</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>The media coverage of the 1925 Scopes Trial, particularly H.L. Mencken's satirical reporting, revealed deep urban-rural cultural divisions in America. Urban newspapers often portrayed the trial as a conflict between modern scientific thinking and rural religious fundamentalism, mocking small-town values and religious beliefs while highlighting the growing cultural gap between metropolitan and rural communities.</explanation>
    </question>
